Rating: 4
Okay... I read EVERY review before preparing this dish so I made a few adjustments. Firstly, I stuffed fresh rosemary, tarragon, 1/4 lime (I had no lemons) and garlic (about 3-4 cloves per bird) underneath the skin of the hens. Secondly, before roasting the hens in the oven, I cooked them in olive oil on the stove on med-high heat for about 6 min to ensure browning and seal in the flavors. From there, I followed the reciped almost exactly as stated (I cooked it for the first 25 min at 475, then finished it for the last 25 min at 375.) The skin is beautifully browned and crispy, the meat is cooked through and falling off the bone. The garlic stuffed under the skin DEFINITELY imparts flavor to the meat. I am not an eater of skin normally, however, with this recipe has converted me. I do recommend basting every 10 min or so while roasting for added browning and crispiness. The sauce was very flavorful, especially if you deglaze the pan w/ wine or chicken broth and get all of those yummy bits at the bottom of the pan out. Pretty easy to make, it just requires a little prep time. I cooked the birds in the oven on top of small pre-cooked potatoes (since I don't have a roasting rack) and surrounded the birds w/ pre-cooked carrots, turnips and parsnips which I believe added a nice sweetness to the sauce. I served the birds w/ (sorry Betty, Martha and Julia) Stove Top chicken stuffing that I doctored up by adding sliced almonds, raisins and chopped waterchestnuts to. DELISH! (I hate people who say delish all the time, like Rachel Ray.) But really, delish! Chicken is falling off the bone, presentation is great, skin crispy and perfectly browned. You can't miss with this. It seems pretty fail-safe to me. And this was even my first time cooking cornish hens... and I have a knack for screwing up recipes. The house has smelled heavenly all afternoon to boot! Would be wonderful (and easy) for a dinner party w/ the right sides.

